{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489545"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:20:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:20:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"686"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/686"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.12,0.19,0.56,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65235"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/686"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50672"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44978"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65235"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about his risk of developing colorectal cancer. His paternal uncle died two years ago at the age of 60 due to metastatic colorectal cancer. His maternal grandmother also died from colorectal cancer, which was diagnosed when she was 70. His father, who is 55, has recently been diagnosed with colorectal cancer. He was told his father\u0027s cancer was tested for specific abnormal genes but was negative. This young man is currently asymptomatic and has no significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colonoscopy now","Biennial faecal occult blood test starting age 35","Biennial faecal occult blood test starting age 45","Five-yearly colonoscopy starting age 45","Refer to family cancer clinic"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a significant family history of colorectal cancer, which places him at increased risk for developing the disease. Risk stratification is crucial in determining the appropriate screening pathway for individuals with a family history of colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has one first-degree relative (his father) diagnosed with colorectal cancer before the age of 60. It is likely that his father underwent testing for mismatch repair genes in keeping with Lynch syndrome, which were negative. The patient would therefore be classified as category 2 (moderate risk) for colorectal cancer, with the most appropriate screening recommendation being \u003Cstrong\u003Efive-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 45\u003C/strong\u003E, 10 years before the age his first-degree relative was diagnosed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy now\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as the patient is asymptomatic and only 25 years old. Regular screening should begin at age 45 unless symptoms develop or there are other indications for earlier investigation.  The risks of unnecessary colonoscopy screening outweighs any benefits of early colonoscopies at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiennial faecal occult blood test starting age 35\u003C/strong\u003E was the recommendation of previous screening guidelines, however new guidelines around risk stratification based on family history were released in 2023 with slightly modified guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiennial faecal occult blood test starting age 45\u003C/strong\u003E are not appropriate for this patient. These screening methods are typically recommended for average-risk individuals in the general population. However, this patient\u0027s family history places him in a moderate-risk category, requiring more intensive screening at an earlier age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring to a family cancer clinic\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered, however is generally recommended for patients in category 3 (high risk) with at least 2 first-degree relatives diagnosed with CRC.  It is not currently strongly recommended for category 2 patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current colorectal cancer risk categories and screening recommendations based on family history are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 1 - similar risk as the general population\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with no family history of colorectal cancer OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne 1st-degree relative with CRC \u226560 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: FOBT should be completed every 2 years from 45 years old as per usual screening protocol. Colonoscopy is generally not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 2 - moderately increased risk of at least 2 - 4 times higher than average\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with one 1st-degree relative CRC diagnosed \u226460 years OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age or one 1st-degree and two 2nd-degrees at any age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: Colonoscopy should be offered 5 yearly starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest diagnosis of CRC in a 1st-degree relative, or age \u003Cstrong\u003E50 \u003C/strong\u003E(whichever is earliest).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 3 - high risk of 4 - 20 times higher than average, excluding hereditary cancer syndromes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic with two 1st-degree and one 2nd-degree relative with colorectal cancer, with at least one diagnosed before 50 years old OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives and two or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed with CRC at any age OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThree or more 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: refer to the familial cancer clinic for genetic assessment before a screening decision is made if Lynch syndrome has not been excluded. If Lynch syndrome is excluded, colonoscopy should be offered every 5 years starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest age of diagnosis of colorectal cancer in a first-degree relative or age \u003Cstrong\u003E40 \u003C/strong\u003Eyears (whichever is earliest)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with a family history of colorectal cancer need to be risk stratified to determine their screening process.","Category 2 (moderate risk) individuals with one first-degree relative diagnosed with colorectal cancer before age 60 should undergo earlier and more frequent colorectal cancer screening.","Category 3 patients have multiple first-degree relatives diagnosed with colorectal cancer"],"references":["RACGP. Guidance for preventative activities in general practice: colorectal cancer. 2024. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/colorectal-cancer","Cancer Council Australia. Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer: Risk and screening based on family history. 2024. Available at: https://app.magicapp.org/#/guideline/jz5DdE"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50672"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"686"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50672"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T22:28:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T22:29:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"686"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65235"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25",